E. COLI EHEC - USA (11): (TENNESSEE) O157, DAY CARE
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 25 Apr 2012
Source: WVLT [edited]
http://www.volunteertv.com/home/headlines/E_coli_found_in_3_kids_who_attend_same_Cocke_Co_day_care_148886855.html


Officials with the Tennessee Department of Health have confirmed cases of _Escherichia coli_ O157 infection in 3 children who attend the same Cocke County day care facility. A spokesperson for the agency, Shelly Walker, said their investigation is still ongoing and they have not yet determined the source of the outbreak.

Walker said that the owner of the day care is cooperating fully with the agency's investigation and all of the families of children who attend the day care have been notified. She added the health department has not asked the center to close, but have asked that any sick children not attend while they are still showing symptoms of being sick.

All 3 children were forced to go to the hospital as a result of the outbreak, but Walker was not able to give their current status.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not clear at this point whether the cluster of EHEC (enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_) in this day care center is related to a food product ingested there or caused by introduction of the organism into the center by a toddler. The infection can spread relatively easily from infant to infant in this center and secondary cases can also occur in siblings in the home. - Mod.LL

Tennessee can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/2h2f. Cocke County can be seen on the map at http://www.digital-topo-maps.com/county-map/tennessee.shtml. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
